[h1]PEP[/h1]

[b]Python Enhancement Proposals (PEP) [/b]are suggestions for improvements to the language, made by experienced Python developers. 
[b]PEP 8[/b] is a style guide on the subject of writing readable code. It contains a number of guidelines in reference to variable names, which are summarized here:
 - modules should have short, all-lowercase names; 
 - class names should be in the CapWords style; 
 - most variables and function names should be lowercase_with_underscores; 
 - constants (variables that never change value) should be CAPS_WITH_UNDERSCORES;
 - names that would clash with Python keywords (such as 'class' or 'if') should have a trailing underscore.

[b]PEP 8[/b] also recommends using spaces around operators and after commas to increase readability. 
[note]However, whitespace should not be overused. For instance, avoid having any space directly inside any type of brackets.[/note]
